{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5bfaa2f1-ee47-4a83-b52f-4fafcf2fd0e1","content":"CLR activation logs won't help here — they only capture how the .NET runtime itself is **loaded** (e.g., which CLR version the shim selects). A `NullReferenceException` is an **application-level** bug that occurs after the runtime is already running.\n\nTo diagnose your crash, consider these approaches instead:\n\n1. **Stack trace** — Check the exception's stack trace (console output, Event Viewer, or crash dump) to find exactly which line dereferences `null`.\n2. **Crash dump** — Capture a dump at crash time and analyze with `dotnet-dump analyze` or WinDbg (`!pe` to print the exception).\n3. **Logging** — Add structured logging around startup to narrow down which object is `null`.\n4. **Debugger** — Attach a debugger and enable \"Break on CLR Exceptions\" for `System.NullReferenceException`.\n\nWould you like help with any of these? For example, I can help you **set up crash dump collection** or walk through **analyzing a dump** if you have one.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3449e9d8-d33e-4e40-bbdf-b6ce89556d3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException. However, CLR activation logs are specifically about how the CLR (Common Language Runtime) is loaded/activated by mscoree.dll — they deal with runtime selection, not application-level exceptions like NullReferenceException.\n\nLet me check if the `clr-activation-debugging` skill is relevant here. Its description says it \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\" It's for when \"the shim picks the wrong runtime, fails to load any runtime, shows unexpected .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand (FOD) dialogs\" etc.\n\n\nA NullReferenceException is an application-level bug that won't show up in CLR activation logs — those logs only capture runtime loading and selection. I should clarify this distinction and suggest more appropriate debugging approaches instead.","outputTokens":514},"id":"cf4f0b7d-abbb-406a-ab0f-4cc742817978","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:11:39.132Z","parentId":"c8a6acc9-f89a-4239-9e54-388c2e97995f"}
